Transform Coordinate System

# Alaska Albers correction is the most common for this region
# More here: https://spatialreference.org/ref/epsg/?page=1
ak_regions_3338 <- ak_regions %>%
    st_transform(crs = 3338)

Plot Transformed Data

plot(ak_regions_3338)

Spatial Joins

pop <- read_csv("data/alaska_population.csv")
## Rows: 323 Columns: 5
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): city
## dbl (4): year, lat, lng, population
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
pop_4326 <- st_as_sf(pop, 
                     coords = c("lng","lat"),
                     crs = 4326,
                     remove = FALSE)

head(pop_4326)
## Simple feature collection with 6 features and 5 fields
## Geometry type: POINT
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -176.6581 ymin: 51.88 xmax: -154.1703 ymax: 62.68889
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
## # A tibble: 6  6
##    year city       lat   lng population             geometry
##   <dbl> <chr>    <dbl> <dbl>      <dbl>          <POINT []>
## 1  2015 Adak      51.9 -177.        122    (-176.6581 51.88)
## 2  2015 Akhiok    56.9 -154.         84 (-154.1703 56.94556)
## 3  2015 Akiachak  60.9 -161.        562 (-161.4314 60.90944)
## 4  2015 Akiak     60.9 -161.        399 (-161.2139 60.91222)
## 5  2015 Akutan    54.1 -166.        899 (-165.7731 54.13556)
## 6  2015 Alakanuk  62.7 -165.        777 (-164.6153 62.68889)
# Will throw an error because we need to convert our CRS data
# pop_joined <- st_join(pop_4326, 
#                       ak_regions_3338, 
#                       join = st_within)
pop_3338 <- st_transform(pop_4326, crs = 3338)
pop_joined <- st_join(pop_3338, ak_regions_3338, join = st_within)
pop_region <- pop_joined %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    group_by(region) %>%
    summarise(total_pop = sum(population))

head(pop_region)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   region           total_pop
##   <chr>                <dbl>
## 1 Aleutian Islands      8840
## 2 Arctic                8419
## 3 Bristol Bay           6947
## 4 Chignik                311
## 5 Cook Inlet          408254
## 6 Copper River          2294
class(pop_region) # Need to convert to be an sf object
## [1] "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"
pop_region_3338 <- left_join(ak_regions_3338, pop_region, by = "region")

class(pop_region_3338)
## [1] "sf"         "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"
plot(pop_region_3338["total_pop"])

pop_mgmt_338 <- pop_region_3338 %>%
    group_by(mgmt_area) %>%
    summarize(total_pop = sum(total_pop))

plot(pop_mgmt_338["total_pop"])

pop_mgmt_3338 <- pop_region_3338 %>%
    group_by(mgmt_area) %>%
    summarize(total_pop = sum(total_pop), do_union = FALSE)

plot(pop_mgmt_3338["total_pop"])

write_sf(pop_region_3338, "data/ak_regions_population.shp")

Visualize with ggplot

ggplot(pop_region_3338) +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = total_pop)) +
    labs(fill = "Total Population") +
    scale_fill_continuous(low = "khaki",
                          high =  "firebrick",
                          labels = comma) +
    theme_bw()

Add rivers spatial data

rivers_3338 <- read_sf("data/ak_rivers_simp.shp")
st_crs(rivers_3338)

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = pop_region_3338, aes(fill = total_pop)) +
  geom_sf(pop_3338, mapping = aes()) +
  geom_sf(data = rivers_3338, aes(linewidth = StrOrder)) +
  scale_linewidth(range = c(0.05, 0.5), guide = "none")
